# Load Testing Results Analysis — YOVI (en2b)

**Course:** Software Architecture (ASW 25-26) · **Lab 9** — Load testing · Other tests
**System under test:** YOVI (`yovi_en2b`), deployed at [`https://micrati.com`](https://micrati.com)
**Tool:** Gatling 3.10.5 · Java DSL
**Reports analysed:**
- `InteropSimulation` — run of 2026-04-24 18:08:01 GMT, duration 2 m 59 s
- `RecordedSimulation` — run of 2026-04-24 18:23:31 GMT, duration 3 m 13 s

---

## 1. Executive summary

Two complementary Gatling simulations were executed against the production deployment of YOVI to evaluate its performance under load:

- **`InteropSimulation`** stresses the **external bot API** (`/interop/games/play`) with four classes of concurrent callers, each invoking a different bot strategy. This is a **white-box** test: every request is deliberately crafted to land on the Rust engine and exercise a known compute cost (random vs. 500 ms minimax vs. 3 000 ms minimax).
- **`RecordedSimulation`** replays a **realistic end-user flow** (login → create a game → play a move → fetch stats) captured from a browser session, executed under a **stepped closed-workload injection profile** (10 → 20 → 30 concurrent users, 60 s each) so that the server dictates throughput and the system's capacity curve is readable.

**Headline findings:**

1. **Zero failed requests across both simulations** (6 986 total requests, 0 KOs). No 5xx errors, no 4xx errors on any endpoint that should have returned 2xx. All deployed services stayed up for the whole test.
2. **The bottleneck is the Rust engine under `smart_bot` on the worst-case position** (empty size-9 board, 45 cells, full 3 000 ms minimax budget). This is the only request that consistently pushed the interop → gamey chain beyond its 2 000 ms timeout, generating 503 rejections. **The web app never reaches the engine in this state**, because a pie-rule size-9 match is not possible in the default UI flow; the bot API is the only way to trigger it.
3. **Under realistic user load (up to 30 concurrent users)** the full vertical stack (Nginx → webapp → users-service → game-service → Rust engine) stayed stable with **p50 flat at ≈ 200 ms and p95 < 650 ms**. Throughput scaled linearly with concurrency (11.8 → 23.4 → 35.4 req/s as users went 10 → 20 → 30). **No saturation point was reached** inside the tested range.
4. The two findings combined show that the system's **practical capacity is gated by the Rust engine, not by the TypeScript services or the database**. Users never collide on the same expensive engine call during normal play because every game session is serialised (one move at a time per user); external bots calling `/interop/games/play` concurrently on large boards is the only realistic way to trigger 503s.

