### 3.4 The 2 000 ms ceiling — what the worst-second percentile means

The interop service's code (`interop/src/services/gameService.ts`) sets `RUST_TIMEOUT_MS = 2000`. Every time the Rust engine does not return within 2 s, the interop service emits:

```json
{ "code": "ENGINE_TIMEOUT", "message": "The bot engine did not respond in time." }
```

with HTTP status 503. In the trajectory above, **51 out of 174 active seconds (29.3 %) experienced at least one response ≥ 2 000 ms**. These are not network outliers — they are the interop's timeout firing. This is the most important single number in the report: under 14 concurrent VUs, the engine overflows its 2 s deadline about once every three seconds.

### 3.5 Per-group analysis — bottleneck localisation

The assertion table (30 rows, all `OK` at 0 % failed events because a 503 is not a KO in this simulation) lists which groups **existed** in the run. Every group that produced at least one 503 shows up as a separate `*_503` assertion. The distribution tells us exactly where the bottleneck is:

| Group | Had 503s? | Interpretation |
|---|:---:|---|
| `RandomBot / A1` (empty size-4) | ✓ | Overflow-driven — engine was starved by concurrent C4 |
| `RandomBot / A2` (mid-game size-4) | ✓ | Same — collateral damage |
| `FastBot / B1` (empty size-5) | ✓ | Expected: 500 ms minimax contends for the same CPU |
| `FastBot / B2` (mid-game size-5) | ✓ | Same |
| `FastBot / B3` (empty size-6) | ✓ | Same, worst fast_bot case |
| **`SmartBot / C1`** (empty size-4) | **✗** | **No 503** — trivial board, sub-budget |
| **`SmartBot / C2`** (near-win size-4) | **✗** | **No 503** — alpha-beta prunes quickly |
| **`SmartBot / C3`** (mid-game size-6) | **✗** | **No 503** — occupied cells shrink the tree |
| **`SmartBot / C4`** (empty size-9, 45 cells) | **✓** | **The bottleneck** — full 3 000 ms budget always consumed |
| `Default / D1` (empty size-4, no bot_id) | ✓ | Collateral — default strategy competes for engine |
| `Default / D2` (size-9 early-game, no bot_id) | ✓ | Same, larger board |

**The bottleneck is not "the Rust engine" — it is specifically the combination of `smart_bot` + a large empty board**. C4 is the only smart_bot request that ever fails, and the 503s on every other group are collateral: while a C4 request is occupying a gamey worker, all other concurrent requests wait and eventually time out at the interop side, even if they only needed 5 ms of CPU themselves.

This is the classic head-of-line blocking pattern of a single-threaded or lightly-threaded compute backend. The scenario is reproducible (on purpose: C4 was designed to be the worst case) and the 29 % 503 rate observed is the direct experimental measurement of this limit.

