## 4. Simulation 2 — `RecordedSimulation`

### 4.1 Purpose

Measure the **user-perceived** behaviour of the full vertical stack under realistic traffic shapes. The scenario was captured with Gatling Recorder from a real browser session on `https://micrati.com` and trimmed to the critical business path:

```
login  →  static assets  →  create game  →  play move 1  →  fetch stats
```

Move 1 is always a valid placement on a freshly-created empty board, so no 409 is possible; any non-2xx/201 on `/game/api/games/*/move` would be a real bug. Only one move per user is played, so under load every VU performs exactly one round-trip against the Rust engine (via the `game` service). Client-side "think pauses" originally recorded at 5–11 s were trimmed to 2 s each so that the closed model can actually exert load during the test window.

### 4.2 Injection profile

Stepped **closed workload** (replaces the earlier `rampUsers(50).during(30 s)` open model):

```java
scn.injectClosed(
  constantConcurrentUsers(10).during(Duration.ofSeconds(60)),
  constantConcurrentUsers(20).during(Duration.ofSeconds(60)),
  constantConcurrentUsers(30).during(Duration.ofSeconds(60))
)
```

The closed model guarantees that a new virtual user is only started when an existing one completes the scenario. The server's own throughput, not Gatling's schedule, therefore dictates the request rate — which is exactly what is needed to read capacity off the latency-vs-concurrency curve without queue inflation distorting the numbers.

