## 7. Measurement caveats

In the interest of traceability:

- **Source data.** All numbers in this document were derived from the `index.html` of each Gatling report. The per-request breakdown tables that Gatling normally renders come from `js/stats.js`, which was not available for this analysis; per-group rollups are inferred from the assertion table. Time-series figures (per-second p50/p75/…/max, throughput, active users) are full-fidelity because they are embedded directly in `index.html`.
- **Percentile aggregation method.** "Typical p95" in the tables is the *median across 180 per-second p95 values*, not the simulation-wide p95 over all individual requests. It is a conservative estimate of what a typical second in the simulation looked like. The worst-second numbers are real extrema.
- **Production dataset.** The user accounts fed to the login step (`users.json`, circular) were shared across VUs. This is adequate for authentication load (JWT is stateless) but means stats reads contend on a small set of DB rows. Cold-cache behaviour on a bigger user base may differ.
- **Network.** All traffic was HTTPS via Nginx; TLS handshake cost is included in every measurement. Running against `http://localhost` directly would remove this cost and produce lower numbers that would not reflect production.

